article.headline: Gillom comes up big against Utah's 7-foot-2 center
article.linkText: Gillom's late baskets propel Mercury past Starzz
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- Even against one of the Phoenix Mercury's biggest
rivals, Jennifer Gillom's heart wasn't in the game until crunch
time.

	   Then her instincts took over.

	   Gillom, who considered sitting out because of the death of her
family dog the night before, made two fadeaways in the lane against
Utah's 7-foot-2 Margo Dydek that sent the Mercury to a 71-66
victory over the Utah Starzz on Saturday night.

	   ``When it's time to show up, I show up,'' said Gillom, who turns
38 this month. ``They were looking for me at the end. They had
confidence in me, and I have confidence in myself.''

	   Gillom had three rebounds, the first making her the 10th player
with 800 rebounds in the 6-year-old WNBA. She has been Phoenix's
scoring leader four of five years -- the only exception being Brandy
Reed in 2000.

	   Reed, who missed the preseason because of an ankle sprain,
played 13 minutes and had four points in her first game for the
Mercury since last year's opener. She was suspended from the second
game after rebelling against the league's salary for veterans.

	   ``We got some players off the injured list back,'' coach Cynthia
Coooper said. ``That helped. Then Adrain -- that's the Adrain
Williams I've been looking for.''

	   After Lisa Harrison broke a 62-62 tie with a free throw with
4:06 remaining, Gillom backed away from Dydek and hit an 8-footer
with 2:44 to go. Forty-eight seconds later, she made another for a
67-64 lead.

	   Rookie Tracy Reid had 16 points to lead the Mercury (1-1), and
Gillom, Williams and Gordana Grubin scored 12 apiece.

	   Williams tied her career highs in points and rebounds (10) and
set a career high with four assists as the Mercury improved to 4-2
in home openers.

	   ``We dug ourselves a hole that was tough to get out of playing
in the home opener for somebody,'' said Adrienne Goodson, who had
18 points and seven rebounds for the Starzz (2-1). Dydek had 15 and
six blocks and Natalie Williams had 10 points and 12 rebounds.

	   Adrain Williams had two rebounds in the final 1:34, the second a
rebound after a miss by Gillom with 16 seconds left that led to
Williams' two free throws for the final score.

	   ``Margo is 7-2 and I'm 6-4, so that's a big difference,''
Williams said. ``Some things work against her and some don't. The
first half I tried a fadeaway, and that didn't work, so they kept
telling me, 'Go under, go under,' and I tried to concentrate on
that.''

	   Utah led three times in the second half, opening a 59-54 lead on
Goodson's layup with 6:40 to play.

	   Phoenix responded on a 3-pointer by Gillom 20 seconds later,
Harrison's jumper that tied it at 59 with 6:00 left and a 3-pointer
by Adriana Moises with 5:11 to go for a 62-60 lead.

	   The Mercury opened two-point leads with their first seven
baskets, and Utah came back to tie it six times.

	   Phoenix took a 16-12 lead when Adrain Williams put back her
missed shot with 9:41 left in the first half, but the Starzz took
their only lead of the first half, 19-18, when Jennifer Azzi made a
3-pointer at the 8:45 mark, and Natalie Williams sank two free
throws 2:00 later.

	   The Mercury shot ahead 31-19 with a 13-0 run that began with a
3-pointer by Grubin and ended with Reid's third basket of the surge
with 3:05 remaining.

	   ``We just didn't come out aggressively to start the game on
either end,'' Starzz coach Candi Harvey said. ``I thought we were a
little passive against a team like this on the road.''
